<p>In the latest development, the U.S. military detained survivors after striking a suspected drug-smuggling vessel in the Caribbean near Venezuela, marking the sixth known operation since early September and the first to leave people alive in custody [washingtonpost.com#1][theguardian.com#1][cbsnews.com#1][thehindu.com#1]. President Trump confirmed the action, describing the target as a &quot;narco-submarine&quot; and framing it as part of a broader effort to disrupt trafficking networks in the region [theguardian.com#1][rt.com#1][firstpost.com#1][dw.com#1]. U.S. officials have not publicly detailed the survivors’ status or next steps, though they are in U.S. custody [washingtonpost.com#1]. The administration’s claim that such strikes save tens of thousands of American lives has not been supported with evidence, drawing scrutiny from independent media, while some observers warn the growing tempo of operations risks wider confrontation with Venezuela [aljazeera.com#1][abc.net.au#1].</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/A3BAvGgNiqYfU2HCgzfEQF_TH6P4gzeNdsV92P6Vqgq-UvuFFBzIvWM_0HTZ6NxgpVuXexaqk7czVuUtk3oUyUsIsdTr9Mlhe18hFBMMPl2yQFQywloNuJtNaJs2CTxpHyExV0pny7dGKWd8LlVS3ipbZE91Wb9tEtP8WxYUPus7SnWqCZqzoVGjYQ4dbtR9Rl8q-LJKGbyKT0Jse0C5yUq2X6BWHc9T9YFkshgVExSx7HF7afEahwkwkQ' alt='President Trump has stepped up maritime and covert operations aimed at Venezuela-linked trafficking networks.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Detainees identified: Two individuals survived the strike and are being held aboard a U.S. Navy ship in the Caribbean, according to reports citing U.S. officials [dw.com#1][mercopress.com#1].</li><li>Target profile: Previous recent actions reportedly destroyed at least five surface vessels since September, while this latest operation targeted a submersible craft [rt.com#1].</li><li>Evidence gap: The administration’s recurring claim that each strike saves 25,000 U.S. lives has not been accompanied by evidence and remains unverifiable [aljazeera.com#1].</li><li>Escalation risk: Analysts and commentators caution that repeated maritime strikes could increase the chance of a broader conflict with Venezuela [abc.net.au#1].</li><li>Diplomatic signals: President Trump said Venezuela’s Nicolás Maduro has made major concessions to ease tensions, though details were not disclosed [firstpost.com#2].</li></ul><blockquote>We attacked a submarine, and that was a drug-carrying submarine built specifically for the transportation of massive amounts of drugs. - President Donald Trump</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>United States (White House): The President characterized the vessel as a purpose-built drug-carrying submarine and emphasized it was not an innocent group. (<a href='https://www.rt.com/news/626639-trump-venezuela-drug-submarine/'>RT</a>)</li><li>Venezuelan government: President Nicolás Maduro rejected what he called CIA-led coups in the region and called for peace. (<a href='https://www.rt.com/news/626639-trump-venezuela-drug-submarine/'>RT</a>)</li><li>Al Jazeera analysis: Claims that each strike saves 25,000 U.S. lives lack publicly provided evidence and cannot be independently verified. (<a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2025/10/18/does-each-boat-strike-off-the-coast-of-venezuela-save-25000-us-lives'>Al Jazeera</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/oct/17/survivors-caribbean-boat-strike-us-military-custody'>US has seized survivors of attack on alleged narco-sub in Caribbean</a> - theguardian.com</li><li><a href='https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2025/10/17/boat-strike-survivors-detained-venezuela-caribbean/'>U.S. military detains survivors of latest boat strike near Venezuela</a> - washingtonpost.com</li><li><a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2025/10/18/does-each-boat-strike-off-the-coast-of-venezuela-save-25000-us-lives'>Does each boat strike off the coast of Venezuela save 25,000 US lives?</a> - aljazeera.com</li><li><a href='https